  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If you are selling a unit or townhouse in Queensland, a body corporate records search will be ordered during the sale process. In most cases it is the buyer's solicitor who orders it as part of their due diligence, and the buyer who pays for it. But you, as the seller, have just as much reason to read it first. What the search reveals directly affects how your property is priced, how buyers respond to it, and whether a contract survives the finance and due diligence period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a body corporate records search is</h2>
      <p>A body corporate records search is a formal inspection of the body corporate's financial and administrative records for the community titles scheme in which your lot sits. It is ordered through the body corporate manager, who arranges access to the scheme's files, and the results are provided to whoever ordered the search, typically in a report prepared by a search company.</p>

      <p>The search is not an inspection of your individual unit. It covers common property and the scheme as a whole. Its purpose is to give a buyer's solicitor an accurate picture of the financial health and administrative history of the body corporate before their client commits to buying.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is included in a full records search</h2>
      <p>A full body corporate records search covers a standard set of documents and disclosures. The most significant are:</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">AGM and committee meeting minutes:</strong> Typically the two most recent years of annual general meeting minutes and any committee meeting minutes during that period. These are the primary source of narrative about the building: what maintenance has been done, what was discussed, what was approved, what problems were raised and how they were handled. A buyer's solicitor will read these carefully. Red flags include recurring disputes, deferred maintenance, unresolved structural complaints, and contentious votes.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Administration fund and sinking fund balances:</strong> The current balance of both funds. The administration fund covers day-to-day running costs: garden maintenance, cleaning, insurance premiums, management fees. The sinking fund covers long-term capital works: painting, roof repairs, lift replacement, pool resurfacing. A healthy sinking fund balance means the scheme is financially prepared for future capital expenditure without needing to raise a special levy. A deficit or a very low balance is a material concern for any buyer.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Recent financial statements:</strong> The body corporate's operating accounts, typically for the previous financial year. These show whether levies are being collected and spent appropriately and whether there are any unusual financial patterns.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance certificate of currency:</strong> Confirmation that the building's insurance for common property is current, what it covers, and the insured sum. Most buyers' solicitors will check that the building is adequately insured and that the policy is not lapsed or overdue for renewal.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Current or pending legal proceedings:</strong> Any litigation or tribunal proceedings involving the body corporate, whether as plaintiff or defendant. This includes disputes with owners, contractors, or third parties. Active litigation is a material fact that sellers must disclose and that can cause buyers to withdraw or renegotiate.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Outstanding levies on any lots:</strong> Whether any lot in the scheme has unpaid levies. If unpaid levies are attached to your lot, they must be resolved at settlement. Outstanding levies on other lots indicate financial stress in the scheme.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Current or proposed special levies:</strong> Any special levy that has been passed or is under active consideration by the committee. A special levy is an additional charge raised on all owners, typically to fund a capital works expense that the sinking fund cannot cover. A passed special levy is a certain cost. A proposed but not yet passed special levy is a risk that buyers factor into their offer.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Notices of major upcoming maintenance works:</strong> Any formal notices about significant common property works planned for the near future. If the building is scheduled for external painting, roof replacement, or structural repairs, buyers want to know before they sign.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The by-laws of the scheme:</strong> The rules that govern what owners can and cannot do within the scheme. By-laws cover matters such as pet ownership, parking, noise, renovations, and short-term letting. Buyers review by-laws to understand what they are agreeing to and whether anything conflicts with their intended use of the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who orders it and who pays</h2>
      <p>In the standard Queensland unit sale, the buyer's solicitor orders the records search as part of the due diligence period under the contract. The cost, typically $200 to $500 depending on the complexity of the scheme and the strata manager's fees, is paid by the buyer. The search is usually ordered in the first few days after contract signing and the results come back within five to ten business days.</p>

      <p>Sellers are not required to order a records search, but many should. If you are uncertain about the state of the sinking fund, whether a special levy is being considered, or what the recent AGM minutes contain, ordering your own search before you list puts you in control of information that will surface during due diligence anyway. A seller who already understands what is in the records can price with confidence and respond to buyer concerns without being caught off guard.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a clean records search looks like</h2>
      <p>A clean result has several consistent characteristics. The sinking fund balance is healthy relative to the age and size of the building and the known future capital requirements. There are no current or proposed special levies. There is no active litigation involving the body corporate. The AGM minutes show routine business: budget approvals, maintenance planning, insurance renewals, committee elections. The insurance is current and adequate. Levies are up to date on all lots. The by-laws are straightforward and do not contain unusual restrictions.</p>

      <p>A clean result does not guarantee a buyer will not ask questions. But it removes the most common sources of buyer concern and contract renegotiation during the due diligence period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long the search takes</h2>
      <p>Ordering and receiving a records search typically takes five to ten business days. The body corporate manager must arrange access to their files and a search company reviews them. Do not assume this is a same-day or next-day process. If you are ordering your own search before listing, allow at least two weeks before your anticipated listing date so the results are in hand before you go to market.</p>

      <p>If you are in a settlement timeline that is tight, flag this with your solicitor early. A delayed records search is one of the more common causes of settlement extensions in Queensland unit sales.</p>

